<section xml:id="section-assignment5">
  <title>Assignment 5</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Assume that there is a particle with charge <m>q</m> located
        at everyapoint in <m>RR^3</m> which has integer coordinates.
        What is the flux of the electric field over the following
        surfaces? (8) 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li>
          The sphere of radius <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> centred at the origin. 
        </li>
        <li>
          The sphere of radius <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> centred at the point
          <m>\left(0, 0, \frac{1}{2}\right)</m>. 
        </li>
        <li>
          The sphere of radius <m>1</m> centred at the the point 
          <m>\left(\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{2}\right)</m>. 
        </li>
        <li>
          The sphere of radius <m>\frac{5}{2}</m> centred at the origin. 
        </li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>\sigma</m> be the horizontal solid disc of radius
        <m>1</m> centre about the <m></m> axis in the plane
        <m>z=1</m>. Consider a scurrent density in the neighbourhood
        of this disc. (16) 
        <me>
          J = \frac{\sin t}{\mu_0} (z, 0 0) 
        </me>
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Calculate <m>I_\sigma</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Calculate the induced magnetic field. (You have some
            choice here: you need any field with a particular curl.
            Chose the most straightforward vector potential and then
            check that <m>\nabla \cdot B = 0</m> is still satisfied.
            As a hint, you can find a field where both <m>B_1</m> and
            <m>B_3</m> are zero.) 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Calculate <m>\Phi_{B,\sigma}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Calculate the line integral of <m>B</m> around the circle
            <m>\del \sigma</m> in two says: directly and using
            Maxwell's equations. (Make sure, of course, that the two
            calculations agree.) 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        On an open set <m>U</m> in the first octant of <m>\RR^3</m>,
        consider the following forms and vector fields. (Implicitly,
        this open set is treated as a manifold with coordinate
        function <m>\phi = \Id</m>. (16) 
        <md>
          <mrow>
            v_1 \amp = (x^2 + y^2) \del_x + (x^2 + z^2) \del y + (y^2 +
            z^2) \del_z 
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            v_2 \amp = x \del x + y \del y _ z \del z 
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            v_3 \amp = \frac{1}{xyz} \del_x + \frac{1}{xyz} \del y +
            \frac{1}{xyz} \del z 
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            w_1 \amp = x dx + y dx + z dz 
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            w_2 \amp = xy dx \wedge dy + yz dx \wedge dz + z^2 dy
            \wedge dz  
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            w_3 \amp = \frac{1}{x^2 + y^2 + z^2} dx \wedge dy \wedge
            dz 
          </mrow>
        </md>
        Do the following calculations.
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li>
          <me>
            w_1(v_1)
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            w_1(v_2)
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            i_{v_1} w_2
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            w_1 \wedge w_2 
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            i_{v_3} w_2 
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            dw_2 
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            dw_1 
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            w_3 \wedge w_1
          </me>
        </li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        In several parts, this question looks at the generlization of
        curl to <m>\RR^4</m>. (8) 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li>
          Let <m>\omega</m> be a 1-form on an open set in
          <m>\RR^4</m>. Calculate <m>d\omega</m>. Compare the
          components to the components of curl. 
        </li>
        <li>
          Let <m>\omega</m> be a 2-form on an open set in
          <m>\RR^4</m>. Calculate <m>d\omega</m>. Compare the
          components to the components of curl. 
        </li>
        <li>
          Why are both of these calculations a generalization of curl?
        </li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
